# **3.  Problem Statement**

The 75% Metal GPU cap is a macOS safety floor designed for general-purpose consumer use. OpenClaw is a headless server with no display, no GUI applications, and no interactive user sessions on the openclaw account. The OS memory floor required for this workload profile is substantially lower than Apple's conservative general-purpose default.

Staying at the 75% default on the 32GB configuration means a Q4_K_M quantized 32B model (approximately 18-20 GB) loads partially in GPU memory and partially via CPU fallback. Raising the cap to 87.5% (28,672 MB) provides sufficient headroom to load the full model weight in GPU memory with context buffer capacity remaining.

On the 64GB configuration the 75% default provides 49,152 MB. Raising to 90% (58,982 MB) increases headroom for larger model weights and longer context windows without approaching the OS starvation threshold.

# **4.  Allocation Policy**

Two configurations are fully specified. The operator selects the applicable row on setup day based on hardware purchased.

| **Config** | **Total** | **GPU Allocation** | **OS Reserve** | **Effective %** | **MB Value** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 32 GB | 32,768 MB | 28,672 MB | ~4,096 MB (~4 GB) | 87.5% | **28672** |
| 64 GB | 65,536 MB | 58,982 MB | ~6,554 MB (~6.4 GB) | 90.0% | **58982** |

The OS reserve values above reflect a headless server profile. No GUI applications, no display server workload, and no interactive user sessions run under the openclaw account. The admin and dev accounts are inactive during normal operation. If the system exhibits memory pressure (swap > 0, memory pressure state yellow or red) the operator must reduce iogpu.wired_limit_mb and update this ADR.

# **5.  Implementation — LaunchDaemon**

The LaunchDaemon approach applies iogpu.wired_limit_mb at boot via launchd without modifying /etc/sysctl.conf. SIP remains intact. The plist is auditable, version-controlled, and reversible without a kernel mode change.

## **5.1  Plist Location and Ownership**

File: /Library/LaunchDaemons/com.openclaw.iogpu.wired_limit.plist

Owner: root:wheel   Permissions: 0644   Written by: admin account on setup day

## **5.2  Plist Content — 32 GB Configuration**

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN"

  "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">

<plist version="1.0">

  <dict>

    <key>Label</key>

    <string>com.openclaw.iogpu.wired_limit</string>

    <key>ProgramArguments</key>

    <array>

      <string>/usr/sbin/sysctl</string>

      <string>iogpu.wired_limit_mb=28672</string>

    </array>

    <key>RunAtLoad</key>

    <true/>

    <key>StandardOutPath</key>

    <string>/var/log/openclaw/iogpu_wired_limit.log</string>

    <key>StandardErrorPath</key>

    <string>/var/log/openclaw/iogpu_wired_limit_error.log</string>

  </dict>

</plist>

For the 64 GB configuration substitute iogpu.wired_limit_mb=58982 on the sysctl argument line. All other plist content is identical.

## **5.3  Setup Day Commands**

Run under the admin account. Substitute the correct MB value for the hardware purchased.

# 1. Create log directory

sudo mkdir -p /var/log/openclaw

sudo chown root:wheel /var/log/openclaw

sudo chmod 755 /var/log/openclaw

# 2. Write plist (use 28672 for 32GB, 58982 for 64GB)

sudo tee /Library/LaunchDaemons/com.openclaw.iogpu.wired_limit.plist << 'EOF'

  [paste plist content from Section 5.2]

EOF

# 3. Set ownership and permissions

sudo chown root:wheel /Library/LaunchDaemons/com.openclaw.iogpu.wired_limit.plist

sudo chmod 0644 /Library/LaunchDaemons/com.openclaw.iogpu.wired_limit.plist

# 4. Load the daemon

sudo launchctl load /Library/LaunchDaemons/com.openclaw.iogpu.wired_limit.plist

# 5. Verify — should return the MB value set above

sysctl iogpu.wired_limit_mb

# **6.  Audit and Logging**

Three log sources provide a complete audit trail for this setting. SIP remains intact throughout.

| **Log Source** | **Location** | **What It Records** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| LaunchDaemon stdout | /var/log/openclaw/iogpu_wired_limit.log | sysctl output on each boot confirming the value applied |
| LaunchDaemon stderr | /var/log/openclaw/iogpu_wired_limit_error.log | Any error output from sysctl at boot — empty on success |
| macOS Unified Log | log show --predicate 'process == "sysctl"' --last boot | Kernel-level record of the sysctl parameter change at boot |

The openclaw log directory (/var/log/openclaw/) is included in the nightly pg_dump backup scope review (ADR-019). Log rotation is not required in Phase 1; files are small (one line per boot).

Verification command — run after each boot to confirm active value:

sysctl iogpu.wired_limit_mb

Expected output for 32 GB config: iogpu.wired_limit_mb: 28672

Expected output for 64 GB config: iogpu.wired_limit_mb: 58982

# **7.  ADR-033 Threshold Amendment**

ADR-033 Section 4 defines unified memory alert thresholds based on the 32GB default configuration with no VRAM allocation change. Those thresholds must be updated to reflect the reduced OS headroom introduced by this ADR. This section constitutes the formal amendment.

| **Config** | **Metric** | **ADR-033 Original** | **ADR-036 Revised** | **Rationale** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 32 GB | mem_used_gb yellow | 28 GB | **26 GB** | OS reserve is ~4 GB; alert when within 2 GB of GPU allocation ceiling |
| 32 GB | mem_used_gb red | 30 GB | **28 GB** | Red at GPU allocation ceiling — any usage above this risks OS starvation |
| 64 GB | mem_used_gb yellow | N/A (not previously defined) | **56 GB** | ~2.5 GB below GPU ceiling; early warning with headroom to act |
| 64 GB | mem_used_gb red | N/A (not previously defined) | **58 GB** | At GPU allocation ceiling — OS starvation risk if crossed |

The hardware_metrics.sql alert view (ADR-034) must be updated on setup day to use the revised thresholds above. The hw_collector.py alert logic is unchanged — it reads thresholds from the view definition.

# **8.  SIP Posture**

System Integrity Protection remains enabled throughout the lifecycle of this ADR. The following table documents the options considered and the rejection rationale for each alternative that would have required SIP modification.

| **Method** | **SIP Required** | **Decision** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| LaunchDaemon plist (this ADR) | No — SIP intact | ADOPTED. Runtime kernel parameter applied via launchd. Auditable, reversible, survives updates. |
| /etc/sysctl.conf modification | Yes — SIP must be disabled | REJECTED. SIP disablement degrades the security posture established in ADR-023 and ADR-032. Risk disproportionate to benefit. |
| Manual sysctl on each boot | No | REJECTED. Requires operator action on every reboot. Not suitable for an unattended headless server. |
| Kernel extension / kext patch | Yes — SIP must be disabled | REJECTED. Unsupported, high risk, not reversible without SIP re-enablement. |

# **9.  Reversal Procedure**

If the system exhibits instability (swap > 0, memory pressure red, thermal stress, kernel panic) the operator reverses this setting in two steps:

Step 1 — Immediate (no reboot required):

sudo sysctl iogpu.wired_limit_mb=0

This resets the GPU cap to the macOS 75% default immediately. No reboot required. Takes effect within seconds.

Step 2 — Prevent reapplication on next reboot:

sudo launchctl unload /Library/LaunchDaemons/com.openclaw.iogpu.wired_limit.plist

To permanently remove the setting:

sudo rm /Library/LaunchDaemons/com.openclaw.iogpu.wired_limit.plist

On reboot without the LaunchDaemon, the system returns to the macOS default (75% cap). No kernel modification, no SIP change, and no data loss occurs at any stage of reversal.

If the 32 GB configuration is unstable at 87.5% (28,672 MB), reduce to 85% (27,648 MB) before attempting full reversal. Intermediate values may provide stable operation at a reduced but still above-default GPU allocation.

# **10.  NIST 800-53 Alignment**

| **Control** | **Title** | **Status** | **Implementation** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| SA-2 | Allocation of Resources | MET | GPU memory allocation explicitly planned and documented. MB values and OS reserve rationale recorded per configuration. |
| SC-5 | Denial of Service Protection | IMPROVED | Increased GPU headroom reduces probability of model load failure causing agent denial-of-service. Swap > 0 alert (ADR-033) detects OS starvation before it becomes a service failure. |
| SI-4 | System Monitoring | MET (extended) | hw_collector.py monitors mem_used_gb and mem_swap_gb at 60-second intervals. Revised thresholds (Section 7) reflect actual OS headroom post-allocation. |
| SI-4(5) | System-Generated Alerts | MET | Swap > 0 triggers critical Telegram alert. Memory pressure red triggers alert. Both conditions indicate OS starvation risk under the aggressive GPU allocation. |
| AU-2 | Event Logging | MET | LaunchDaemon stdout log records the value applied on each boot. macOS Unified Log records the kernel parameter change independently. |
| AU-3 | Content of Audit Records | MET | Log entries include timestamp, process, parameter name, and value applied. Sufficient for forensic review if a memory-related incident occurs. |

# **11.  Setup Day Sequence**

All steps run under the admin account on setup day. Step 1 is a decision gate — it determines which MB value is used in all subsequent steps.

| **Step** | **Action** | **Account** | **Dependency** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | Confirm hardware configuration (32 GB or 64 GB). Select MB value: 28672 or 58982. | operator | Hardware in hand |
| 2 | Create /var/log/openclaw/ directory with root:wheel ownership and 755 permissions. | admin | Step 1 complete |
| 3 | Write LaunchDaemon plist to /Library/LaunchDaemons/com.openclaw.iogpu.wired_limit.plist using the MB value selected in Step 1. | admin | Step 2 complete |
| 4 | Set ownership (root:wheel) and permissions (0644) on the plist file. | admin | Step 3 complete |
| 5 | Load the daemon: sudo launchctl load [plist path]. Verify with: sysctl iogpu.wired_limit_mb | admin | Step 4 complete |
| 6 | Test reboot. Verify sysctl iogpu.wired_limit_mb returns the correct value after restart. Check /var/log/openclaw/iogpu_wired_limit.log for boot entry. | admin | Step 5 complete |
| 7 | Update hardware_metrics.sql alert view with revised mem_used_gb thresholds from ADR-036 Section 7. | dev | Step 6 complete, PostgreSQL running |
| 8 | Load first Ollama model (7B Tier 1). Run ollama ps to confirm GPU memory allocation reflects the new ceiling. Record observed value in ADR-031 change log. | openclaw | Step 7 complete, Ollama running |

